WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.360
Welcome back!

2
00:00:02.360 --> 00:00:07.600
In this video, we will review transactions in the capital markets.

3
00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:11.520
Recall from the financial system diagram that lenders sell

4
00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:15.680
their loans to financial institutions in the capital markets.

5
00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:20.960
Financial institutions purchase these loans to earn the interest borrowers pay.

6
00:00:20.960 --> 00:00:26.680
This transaction is known as a trade: they are trading money for loan agreements.

7
00:00:26.680 --> 00:00:31.960
Before we dive into trading, let's first talk about the mortgage market in the US.

8
00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:39.280
In the first quarter of 2023, Americans owed 12 trillion dollars in mortgage debt.

9
00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:44.320
For comparison, the annualized US gross domestic product, a measurement

10
00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:50.880
of total economic activity, was an estimated 25 trillion in the same period.

11
00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:58.080
In addition, mortgage debt makes up almost 75% of all the household debt Americans owe.

12
00:00:58.080 --> 00:01:01.520
So mortgages account for a large portion of the US

13
00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:08.040
debt and economy, and much of the 12 trillion dollars in mortgage debt was traded in the capital markets.

14
00:01:08.040 --> 00:01:13.520
When mortgages are sold to investors, they are often put into groups called "pools".

15
00:01:13.520 --> 00:01:17.000
A pool can be one or more mortgage loans.

16
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.480
There are two types of common transactions in mortgage trades.

17
00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:24.320
The first is a whole loan trade.

18
00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:31.800
A whole loan mortgage transaction is a trade in which an investor individually bids on each mortgage.

19
00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:37.040
This is pretty straightforward, as the investor knows exactly which mortgages they purchase.

20
00:01:37.040 --> 00:01:40.560
However, this type of transaction is inefficient as the

21
00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:45.440
investor needs to analyze each loan, which can be time-consuming.

22
00:01:45.440 --> 00:01:51.080
Securiziation is the most common type of transaction seen in the mortgage capital markets.

23
00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:56.280
With securitizations, mortgage pools are bundled into a new financial asset, called a

24
00:01:56.280 --> 00:02:02.600
mortgage-backed security, and the investor buys the security instead of the individual mortgage.

25
00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:07.800
Securitization allows investors to buy many more mortgages than in whole loan trading,

26
00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:14.320
as they don't have to analyze each mortgage but rather just the performance of the MBS bond.

27
00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:17.800
Securitizations are usually formed from mortgage pools

28
00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:27.400
with similar characteristics, for example, rate, term, loan-to-value, location, or even the lender who originated the loan.

29
00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:32.280
However, not every loan is eligible for securitization, as they need to

30
00:02:32.280 --> 00:02:37.840
meet the requirements set forth by the security creator, known as a securitizer.

31
00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:44.720
These requirements become the qualification guidelines lenders must use to sell their loans to securitizers.

32
00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:49.280
We covered some of those qualification guidelines in the previous chapter.

33
00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:55.080
Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac are two of the largest mortgage securitizers in the US.

34
00:02:55.080 --> 00:03:00.280
They purchase about 70% of all mortgages in the US and pool them into

35
00:03:00.280 --> 00:03:07.080
their securities, which they call "uniform mortgage-backed securities", or UMBS.

36
00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:12.040
This is because all mortgage loans must meet their underwriting guidelines.

37
00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:19.120
Once an investor has identified which mortgage or MBS bond they want, they will place a bid on it with a price.

38
00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:23.840
The trade price is expressed as a percentage of the loan's principal balance.

39
00:03:23.840 --> 00:03:27.560
The trade amount is the total dollar amount paid for the loan.

40
00:03:27.560 --> 00:03:31.160
This is the product of the trade price and principal balance.

41
00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:35.360
Remember that the principal balance is just the current balance of the loan.

42
00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:39.080
The trade premium is the difference between the principal balance and the

43
00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:44.280
trade amount and shows the extra amount the investor paid to own the mortgage.

44
00:03:44.280 --> 00:03:50.320
For example, if a mortgage is trading at a price of 101, it means that the buyer

45
00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:59.280
will pay $101,000 for a $100,000 principal balance, which is a trade premium of $1,000.

46
00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:04.760
Once bids have been received, the seller must decide which investor to transact with.

47
00:04:04.760 --> 00:04:07.200
In this case study, we will replicate a whole loan

48
00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:11.960
transaction, where investors can bid on any individual loan they want.

49
00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:15.000
We'll use a technique to find the highest price.

50
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.840
As a lender, we can choose to sell through a whole loan trade or a securitization,

51
00:04:19.840 --> 00:04:26.520
so we'll compare the whole loan prices to UMBS prices to ensure we're maximizing profit.

52
00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:33.440
Now that you have the trading basics down, it's time to review the bids on our pool and get this trade started.

